Constructors
    -> look like functions but they are not exactly same
    -> their name should exactly match of class name
    -> don't have return type
    -> they are invoked/called/triggered automatically while object creation
    -> You can't invoked again soon after object creation
    A constructor in Java is a special method used to initialize an object.
    It is called automatically when an object is created using the new keyword.


Types of constructors:
    Default constructor –> No parameters.
    Parameterized constructor –> Takes parameters to initialize objects.


Wrapper Classes
    -> wrapper class is a class that converts a primitive data type into an object.

    int num = 10;

    // Autoboxing (primitive to object)
    Integer obj = num;

    // Unboxing (object to primitive)
    int value = obj;

    System.out.println(value);




Collections   (V IMP)
    -> Collections in Java are a framework used to store and manage groups of objects dynamically.
    -> It provides classes and interfaces for efficient data storage and manipulation.
    -> set of classes and interfaces used to store, organize, and manipulate groups of objects efficiently.

ArrayList
    O(1) time complexity -> Arrays and ArrayList
    if "adding at the end" at arraylist is also O(1)
    if "added in the start" it will be linear -> O(n)     (It shifts all elements to right)
    for "searching" the elements it is linear -> O(n)


Generics
    Generics allow you to write classes, interfaces, and methods that work with different data types while providing type safety.
    Eg :- ArrayList<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();
    here only we can use integer type



