ArrayDeque
    -> resizable array implementation of the Deque (Double-Ended Queue) interface.
    -> Deque allows insertion and deletion from both the front and the rear.
    -> It allows insertion and deletion from both ends.
    -> Can be used as both a Queue (FIFO) and a Stack (LIFO).
    -> Does not allow null elements.


HashMap
    -> Key value pairs
    -> should be immutable
    -> keys should be immutable objects
    -> keys are hashed, and can't be duplicate
    -> Values can be anything
    -> O(N)


    ** LOOP we USE here for hashmap, because we don't have index in hashmap **
    for (Map.Entry<Integer, String> entry : map.entrySet()) {       // map.entrySet() -> all key-value pairs.
        System.out.println(entry.getKey() + " : " + entry.getValue());
    }



Linked List
    -> Linear Data Structure
    -> Collection of Nodes connected using pointers
    -> Each Node contains Data and Next Pointer
    -> Head -> First Node
    -> Tail -> Last Node
    -> Dynamic size (No fixed size)
    -> Memory is allocated dynamically
    -> Fast insertion and deletion
    -> Slow random access (No indexing)
    -> Search takes O(N)
    -> Types -> Singly, Doubly, Circular Linked List
    -> Used in Stack, Queue, Graph, HashMap (Chaining)
    -> Last node points to NULL (except Circular Linked List)
    -> Best when frequent insertion and deletion are required

// floyd's algorithm
// ** Cyclic linked list uses Fast and Slow pointers **



